    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Elongated, more-or-less parallel-sided isopod with large bulging eyes and obvious side plates. Some specimens swollen around body segments 4-5. Head crossed by a transverse dorsal furrow behind the eyes. Abdominal segments fused and joined to telson to form an elongate ‘pleotelson’ which is more-or-less parallel–sided with a squared-off end. The pleotelson has one complete segmental division at its base followed by two partial crimp-like ‘sutures’ or partial joints on either side. Colour dark brown, often with silvery metallic sheen.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_6728",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Reaches 30<strong> </strong>mm length, excluding antennae.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_6729",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Cosmopolitan.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Whole region.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_6730",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Usually associated with drifting seaweeds or other debris on the high seas and may be cast ashore after inshore winds, when it can be abundant.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_6731",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Herbivorous.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_6732",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>As with all isopods the eggs are retained in a marsupial pouch between the walking legs of females, where they develop into fully-formed young prior to release.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_6733",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>The metallic sheen is a useful identification feature, but can otherwise be confused with species of the genus <i>Paridotea</i>, which have a similar elongated and parallel-sided body form. <i>Paridotea</i> however, have smaller eyes, lack the groove across the head and often have pointed tips to the corners of the pleotelson.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_6734",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Branch, G, Griffiths, CL, Branch, M & Beckley, L (2016). Two Oceans: A Guide to the Marine Life of Southern Africa (Fourth edition). Struik Nature, Cape Town. (p. 354). <br><br>Kensley, B (1978). Guide to the Marine Isodods of Southern Africa. <i>Trustees of the South African Museum</i>, Cape Town. 173 pp. (p. 38)",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_8_6735",
